As someone who likes both Go and Perl 6, this reminds me a lot of Perl 6 grammars; I look forward to using this in Go. Here&#x27;s a rough equivalent in P6, although I don&#x27;t think the Go one or mine are completely legit in terms of internationalization and whatnot:<p><pre><code>  grammar email-address {
      token TOP { ^ <user> &#x27;@&#x27; <hostname> $ }
      token user { <[ \w \d . _ % + - ]>+ }
      token hostname { <domain> &#x27;.&#x27; <TLD> }
      token domain { \w+ }
      token TLD { \w+ }
  }

  if (my $email = email-address.parse(&#x27;joe@猫.com&#x27;)) {
      say $email<user>;
      say $email<hostname><domain>;
      say $email<hostname><TLD>;
  }
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s also possible to turn the captured parts into their own objects ($email has a type of Match; it&#x27;s not just a hash).
